---
import Layout from '../../layouts/Layout.astro';
import CalculatorCard from '../../components/CalculatorCard.astro';
import FormulaBox from '../../components/FormulaBox.astro';
import FAQSection from '../../components/FAQSection.astro';
import Breadcrumb from '../../components/Breadcrumb.astro';

const faqItems = [
  {
    question: "What is CII?",
    answer: "The Carbon Intensity Indicator (CII) is an IMO metric that rates ships from A to E based on their annual operational carbon intensity — measured as grams of CO₂ per tonne-mile of transport work. It applies to vessels of 5,000 GT and above on international voyages and is part of the IMO's strategy to reduce greenhouse gas emissions from shipping.",
  },
  {
    question: "What happens if my vessel gets a D or E rating?",
    answer: "Vessels rated D for three consecutive years, or E in any year, must submit a Corrective Action Plan (CAP) as part of their Ship Energy Efficiency Management Plan (SEEMP). The plan must describe operational and technical measures to improve the vessel's CII rating to at least C level. Non-compliance can affect vessel operations and charter attractiveness.",
  },
  {
    question: "How can I improve my vessel's CII rating?",
    answer: "CII can be improved through operational measures (speed reduction, weather routing, voyage optimization, hull cleaning, propeller polishing) and technical measures (hybrid propulsion, shore power, energy-saving devices, engine tuning). A combination of measures typically achieves the best results — our CII calculator models improvement scenarios.",
  },
  {
    question: "How do batteries improve CII?",
    answer: "Battery systems reduce annual fuel consumption through hybrid operation, load optimization, and zero-emission port stays. A 15% fuel reduction translates directly to approximately 15% CII improvement. Combined with shore power and operational measures, total CII improvement of 25–35% is achievable, potentially shifting a vessel from D/E to C/B rating.",
  },
  {
    question: "Does CII apply to my vessel?",
    answer: "CII applies to cargo ships, tanker ships, and passenger ships of 5,000 GT and above on international voyages. The specific vessels covered include bulk carriers, oil tankers, container ships, general cargo ships, refrigerated cargo carriers, combination carriers, LNG carriers, and ro-ro passenger ships. Check IMO MARPOL Annex VI for the complete applicability list.",
  },
];
---

<Layout
  title="Understanding CII Ratings and Vessel Carbon Intensity | Battery Calculators"
  description="Complete guide to IMO Carbon Intensity Indicator (CII) ratings covering A–E rating thresholds, factors affecting CII, operational improvements, and how battery and hybrid systems improve vessel carbon intensity."
  canonical="https://batterycalculators.com/learn/understanding-cii-ratings"
  schema="faqPage"
  schemaName="Understanding CII Ratings and Vessel Carbon Intensity"
  schemaDescription="Complete guide to IMO Carbon Intensity Indicator (CII) ratings covering A–E rating thresholds, factors affecting CII, operational improvements, and how battery and hybrid systems improve vessel carbon intensity."
  schemaUrl="https://batterycalculators.com/learn/understanding-cii-ratings"
  faqItems={faqItems}
>
  <div class="max-w-3xl mx-auto">
    <div class="mb-12 border-b border-hairline pb-8">
      <a href="/learn" class="text-label-uppercase text-xs text-muted hover:text-primary transition-colors mb-4 inline-block">&larr; Back to Guides</a>
      <Breadcrumb items={[{ label: "Learning Center", href: "/learn" }, { label: "Understanding CII Ratings" }]} />
      <span class="text-label-uppercase text-m-blue-light text-xs block mb-4">MARINE</span>
      <h1 class="text-display-md text-primary mb-6">Understanding CII Ratings and Vessel Carbon Intensity</h1>
      <p class="text-body-md text-body font-light">
        The Carbon Intensity Indicator (CII) is the IMO's primary operational measure for reducing greenhouse gas emissions from international shipping. Since January 2023, vessels of 5,000 GT and above must calculate and report their annual CII rating — a letter grade from A to E that reflects how efficiently a vessel operates in terms of carbon emissions per unit of transport work. This guide explains how CII works, what the ratings mean, and how vessel operators can improve their scores.
      </p>
    </div>

    <div class="flex flex-col gap-12">
      <section id="what-is-cii">
        <h2 class="text-title-lg text-primary uppercase tracking-wider mb-4">What Is CII?</h2>
        <p class="text-body-md text-body font-light mb-4">
          The Carbon Intensity Indicator is a mandatory IMO regulation under MARPOL Annex VI that measures the operational carbon intensity of ships. Unlike the Energy Efficiency Existing Ship Index (EEXI), which measures design efficiency, CII measures how efficiently a vessel actually operates — accounting for real-world speed, cargo carried, distance traveled, and fuel consumed.
        </p>
        <p class="text-body-md text-body font-light mb-4">
          CII is calculated annually using the vessel's fuel consumption data, distance traveled, and cargo capacity. The result is expressed as grams of CO₂ per tonne-nautical mile (gCO₂/tn-mi) of transport work. This value is then compared against mandatory reduction factors to determine the vessel's letter rating.
        </p>
        <p class="text-body-md text-body font-light mb-4">
          The regulation applies to cargo ships, tanker ships, and passenger ships of 5,000 GT and above operating on international voyages. This includes bulk carriers, oil tankers, container ships, general cargo ships, refrigerated cargo carriers, combination carriers, LNG carriers, and ro-ro cargo ships.
        </p>
      </section>

      <section id="why-it-matters">
        <h2 class="text-title-lg text-primary uppercase tracking-wider mb-4">Why CII Matters</h2>
        <p class="text-body-md text-body font-light mb-4">
          CII is not merely a reporting exercise — it has direct commercial and regulatory consequences. Vessels with poor CII ratings face corrective action requirements, reduced charter attractiveness, and increasing regulatory risk as reduction factors tighten through 2030.
        </p>
        <div class="grid grid-cols-1 md:grid-cols-2 gap-6">
          <CalculatorCard>
            <h4 class="text-primary font-bold mb-2">Charter Market Impact</h4>
            <p class="text-body-sm text-muted">
              Charterers increasingly require CII data in procurement processes. Major charterers (Cargill, Maersk, BHP) favor vessels with A or B ratings. Vessels rated D or E face difficulty securing long-term charters and may receive lower day rates.
            </p>
          </CalculatorCard>
          <CalculatorCard>
            <h4 class="text-primary font-bold mb-2">Regulatory Consequences</h4>
            <p class="text-body-sm text-muted">
              D-rated vessels (3 consecutive years) and E-rated vessels (any year) must submit Corrective Action Plans in their SEEMP. The IMO is considering measures to penalize persistently non-compliant vessels, including potential operational restrictions.
            </p>
          </CalculatorCard>
          <CalculatorCard>
            <h4 class="text-primary font-bold mb-2">Fuel Cost Savings</h4>
            <p class="text-body-sm text-muted">
              Improving CII directly reduces fuel consumption — the largest vessel operating cost. A 20% CII improvement typically translates to 15–20% fuel cost reduction, delivering both regulatory compliance and financial benefit.
            </p>
          </CalculatorCard>
          <CalculatorCard>
            <h4 class="text-primary font-bold mb-2">Tightening Benchmarks</h4>
            <p class="text-body-sm text-muted">
              CII reduction factors increase annually. A vessel rated C today may drop to D by 2026 without improvement measures. The IMO plans 2% annual tightening through 2030, requiring continuous improvement to maintain compliant ratings.
            </p>
          </CalculatorCard>
        </div>
      </section>

      <section id="ratings">
        <h2 class="text-title-lg text-primary uppercase tracking-wider mb-4">A–E Rating Thresholds</h2>
        <p class="text-body-md text-body font-light mb-4">
          The CII rating scale assigns vessels to five letter grades based on how their operational carbon intensity compares to the required reduction line. The thresholds are defined by the IMO as percentage bands around the reference line.
        </p>
        <div class="bg-surface-soft border border-hairline overflow-hidden">
          <table class="w-full text-left text-body-sm">
            <thead>
              <tr class="border-b border-hairline bg-surface-card">
                <th class="p-4 text-label-uppercase text-primary text-xs tracking-wider">Rating</th>
                <th class="p-4 text-label-uppercase text-primary text-xs tracking-wider">Performance Band</th>
                <th class="p-4 text-label-uppercase text-primary text-xs tracking-wider">Action Required</th>
              </tr>
            </thead>
            <tbody class="divide-y divide-hairline">
              <tr>
                <td class="p-4 font-mono text-primary font-bold">A</td>
                <td class="p-4 text-muted">Major superior (&gt;20% below required level)</td>
                <td class="p-4 text-muted">No action required — exemplary performance</td>
              </tr>
              <tr>
                <td class="p-4 font-mono text-primary font-bold">B</td>
                <td class="p-4 text-muted">Minor superior (10–20% below required level)</td>
                <td class="p-4 text-muted">No action required — above compliance threshold</td>
              </tr>
              <tr>
                <td class="p-4 font-mono text-primary font-bold">C</td>
                <td class="p-4 text-muted">Moderate (0–10% below required level)</td>
                <td class="p-4 text-muted">Compliant — meets IMO target</td>
              </tr>
              <tr>
                <td class="p-4 font-mono text-primary font-bold">D</td>
                <td class="p-4 text-muted">Minor inferior (0–10% above required level)</td>
                <td class="p-4 text-muted">Corrective Action Plan required if rated D for 3 consecutive years</td>
              </tr>
              <tr>
                <td class="p-4 font-mono text-primary font-bold">E</td>
                <td class="p-4 text-muted">Major inferior (&gt;10% above required level)</td>
                <td class="p-4 text-muted">Corrective Action Plan required immediately</td>
              </tr>
            </tbody>
          </table>
        </div>
      </section>

      <section id="factors">
        <h2 class="text-title-lg text-primary uppercase tracking-wider mb-4">Factors Affecting CII</h2>
        <p class="text-body-md text-body font-light mb-4">
          CII is influenced by a combination of operational and technical factors. Understanding these factors is the first step toward improvement.
        </p>
        <div class="bg-surface-soft border border-hairline overflow-hidden">
          <table class="w-full text-left text-body-sm">
            <thead>
              <tr class="border-b border-hairline bg-surface-card">
                <th class="p-4 text-label-uppercase text-primary text-xs tracking-wider">Factor</th>
                <th class="p-4 text-label-uppercase text-primary text-xs tracking-wider">Impact on CII</th>
                <th class="p-4 text-label-uppercase text-primary text-xs tracking-wider">Improvement Potential</th>
              </tr>
            </thead>
            <tbody class="divide-y divide-hairline">
              <tr>
                <td class="p-4 text-muted">Voyage speed</td>
                <td class="p-4 text-muted">Higher speed = higher fuel consumption = worse CII</td>
                <td class="p-4 font-mono text-primary">10–20% improvement from 10% speed reduction</td>
              </tr>
              <tr>
                <td class="p-4 text-muted">Cargo utilization</td>
                <td class="p-4 text-muted">Empty or partial loads = more fuel per tonne-mile</td>
                <td class="p-4 font-mono text-primary">5–15% improvement from optimized routing</td>
              </tr>
              <tr>
                <td class="p-4 text-muted">Hull condition</td>
                <td class="p-4 text-muted">Fouled hull increases resistance and fuel consumption</td>
                <td class="p-4 font-mono text-primary">5–10% improvement from hull cleaning</td>
              </tr>
              <tr>
                <td class="p-4 text-muted">Engine efficiency</td>
                <td class="p-4 text-muted">Older engines operate less efficiently</td>
                <td class="p-4 font-mono text-primary">3–8% improvement from engine tuning/upgrade</td>
              </tr>
              <tr>
                <td class="p-4 text-muted">Weather routing</td>
                <td class="p-4 text-muted">Adverse weather increases fuel consumption</td>
                <td class="p-4 font-mono text-primary">3–7% improvement from optimized routing</td>
              </tr>
              <tr>
                <td class="p-4 text-muted">Hybrid / battery systems</td>
                <td class="p-4 text-muted">Reduce total fuel consumption across operating profile</td>
                <td class="p-4 font-mono text-primary">15–30% improvement from hybrid operation</td>
              </tr>
              <tr>
                <td class="p-4 text-muted">Shore power</td>
                <td class="p-4 text-muted">Eliminates generator fuel at berth</td>
                <td class="p-4 font-mono text-primary">5–10% improvement for high-berth-time vessels</td>
              </tr>
            </tbody>
          </table>
        </div>
      </section>

      <section id="operational-improvements">
        <h2 class="text-title-lg text-primary uppercase tracking-wider mb-4">Operational Improvement Strategies</h2>
        <p class="text-body-md text-body font-light mb-4">
          Vessel operators can improve CII through a combination of immediate operational changes and longer-term technical investments. The most effective approach layers multiple measures to achieve cumulative improvement.
        </p>

        <FormulaBox title="CII Improvement Estimation">
          <div class="bg-surface-soft p-4 font-mono text-primary border border-hairline my-2">
            CII Improvement (%) = Σ(Measure Improvement × Implementation Factor)
          </div>
          <p>
            Each improvement measure has a theoretical maximum impact. The implementation factor accounts for real-world constraints — weather, schedule, operational flexibility — that reduce the theoretical benefit. Typical implementation factors range from 0.6 to 0.9 depending on the measure.
          </p>
          <div class="bg-surface-soft p-4 font-mono text-primary border border-hairline my-2">
            Total CII Improvement: 20–35% achievable with combined measures
          </div>
        </FormulaBox>

        <div class="grid grid-cols-1 md:grid-cols-2 gap-6 mt-6">
          <CalculatorCard>
            <h4 class="text-primary font-bold mb-2">Quick Wins (0–6 months)</h4>
            <ul class="flex flex-col gap-1 text-body-sm text-muted">
              <li>• Speed optimization (5–15%)</li>
              <li>• Weather routing (3–7%)</li>
              <li>• Just-in-time arrival (3–5%)</li>
              <li>• Voyage planning optimization (2–5%)</li>
            </ul>
          </CalculatorCard>
          <CalculatorCard>
            <h4 class="text-primary font-bold mb-2">Medium-Term (6–24 months)</h4>
            <ul class="flex flex-col gap-1 text-body-sm text-muted">
              <li>• Hull cleaning and propeller polishing (5–10%)</li>
              <li>• Engine tuning and maintenance (3–8%)</li>
              <li>• Energy-saving devices (3–7%)</li>
              <li>• Trim optimization (2–5%)</li>
            </ul>
          </CalculatorCard>
          <CalculatorCard>
            <h4 class="text-primary font-bold mb-2">Long-Term Investments (2–5 years)</h4>
            <ul class="flex flex-col gap-1 text-body-sm text-muted">
              <li>• Hybrid propulsion systems (15–25%)</li>
              <li>• Shore power connections (5–10%)</li>
              <li>• Battery energy storage (10–20%)</li>
              <li>• Wind-assisted propulsion (5–15%)</li>
            </ul>
          </CalculatorCard>
          <CalculatorCard>
            <h4 class="text-primary font-bold mb-2">Strategic Measures</h4>
            <ul class="flex flex-col gap-1 text-body-sm text-muted">
              <li>• Fleet renewal with efficient new-builds</li>
              <li>• Alternative fuel adoption (LNG, methanol, ammonia)</li>
              <li>• Digital fleet management systems</li>
              <li>• Crew training and awareness programs</li>
            </ul>
          </CalculatorCard>
        </div>
      </section>

      <section id="battery-hybrid-impact">
        <h2 class="text-title-lg text-primary uppercase tracking-wider mb-4">Battery and Hybrid Impact on CII</h2>
        <p class="text-body-md text-body font-light mb-4">
          Battery and hybrid systems are among the most impactful technical measures for CII improvement. They directly reduce annual fuel consumption — the numerator in the CII calculation — through multiple mechanisms:
        </p>
        <div class="bg-surface-soft border border-hairline overflow-hidden">
          <table class="w-full text-left text-body-sm">
            <thead>
              <tr class="border-b border-hairline bg-surface-card">
                <th class="p-4 text-label-uppercase text-primary text-xs tracking-wider">Mechanism</th>
                <th class="p-4 text-label-uppercase text-primary text-xs tracking-wider">CII Contribution</th>
              </tr>
            </thead>
            <tbody class="divide-y divide-hairline">
              <tr>
                <td class="p-4 text-muted">Zero-emission port operation (shore power)</td>
                <td class="p-4 font-mono text-primary">5–10% CII improvement</td>
              </tr>
              <tr>
                <td class="p-4 text-muted">Hybrid low-load optimization</td>
                <td class="p-4 font-mono text-primary">10–20% CII improvement</td>
              </tr>
              <tr>
                <td class="p-4 text-muted">Peak shaving / load leveling</td>
                <td class="p-4 font-mono text-primary">3–8% CII improvement</td>
              </tr>
              <tr>
                <td class="p-4 text-muted">Regenerative energy capture</td>
                <td class="p-4 font-mono text-primary">3–7% CII improvement</td>
              </tr>
              <tr>
                <td class="p-4 text-muted">Combined hybrid + shore power</td>
                <td class="p-4 font-mono text-primary">20–35% total CII improvement</td>
              </tr>
            </tbody>
          </table>
        </div>
        <p class="text-body-md text-body font-light mt-4">
          For a vessel currently rated D, a combined hybrid and shore power installation can shift the rating to C or even B — achieving compliance without reducing speed or cargo capacity. For vessels already rated C, these measures provide headroom against the annual tightening of CII benchmarks through 2030.
        </p>
      </section>

      <div class="grid grid-cols-1 md:grid-cols-2 gap-4">
        <CalculatorCard class="border-m-blue-light">
          <h4 class="text-label-uppercase text-primary text-xs mb-3">Try It</h4>
          <p class="text-body-sm text-muted mb-4">
            Estimate your vessel's CII rating and model improvement scenarios with the CII Calculator.
          </p>
          <a href="/tools/cii-calculator" class="btn-primary text-xs py-3 px-6 inline-block">Open CII Calculator</a>
        </CalculatorCard>
        <CalculatorCard class="border-m-blue-light">
          <h4 class="text-label-uppercase text-primary text-xs mb-3">Try It</h4>
          <p class="text-body-sm text-muted mb-4">
            Quantify the CO₂ reductions from operational and technical improvements.
          </p>
          <a href="/tools/marine-co2-reduction-calculator" class="btn-primary text-xs py-3 px-6 inline-block">Open Marine CO₂ Reduction Calculator</a>
        </CalculatorCard>
      </div>

      <section>
        <h2 class="text-title-lg text-primary uppercase tracking-wider mb-4">Related Articles</h2>
        <div class="grid grid-cols-1 md:grid-cols-2 gap-6">
          <CalculatorCard>
            <a href="/learn/how-hybrid-vessels-reduce-emissions" class="text-primary hover:underline font-bold block mb-2">How Hybrid Vessels Reduce Emissions</a>
            <p class="text-body-sm text-muted">
              Detailed analysis of hybrid system mechanisms for reducing fuel consumption and CII improvement.
            </p>
          </CalculatorCard>
          <CalculatorCard>
            <a href="/learn/maritime-decarbonization-roadmap" class="text-primary hover:underline font-bold block mb-2">Maritime Decarbonization Roadmap</a>
            <p class="text-body-sm text-muted">
              IMO targets, technology pathways, and regulatory timeline for maritime decarbonization.
            </p>
          </CalculatorCard>
          <CalculatorCard>
            <a href="/learn/shore-power-vs-diesel-generators" class="text-primary hover:underline font-bold block mb-2">Shore Power vs Diesel Generators</a>
            <p class="text-body-sm text-muted">
              How shore power eliminates port emissions and contributes to CII improvement.
            </p>
          </CalculatorCard>
          <CalculatorCard>
            <a href="/marine" class="text-primary hover:underline font-bold block mb-2">Marine Electrification Hub</a>
            <p class="text-body-sm text-muted">
              Explore all marine calculators, tools, and resources for vessel decarbonization planning.
            </p>
          </CalculatorCard>
        </div>
      </section>

      <FAQSection items={faqItems} />
    </div>
  </div>
</Layout>
